visitDirections: From Center Rd. turn west on PR 5 (private road), just North of intersection with Notch Rd.Follow to first house on the right, park, follow GPS.
visitHabitatComment: hemlock hardwood stand. Part of dense pool cluster.
visitSpeciesComments: Largest, most productive pool in dense pool cluster. Nice down tree in pool for attachments. small lobe to north cut off at lower water. Extremely tannic water and depth of pool made visibility poor, probably more eggs.

visitDirections: From Center Rd. turn west on PR 5 (private road), just North of intersection with Notch Rd.Follow to first house on the right, park, follow GPS.
visitHabitatComment: Hemlock hardwood stand. Part of large dense pool cluster that spans property boundaries (which are not entirely clear).
visitSpeciesComments: many fern hummocks in pool- royal and cinnamon ferns. ledgy area- dense pool cluster.

visitLocationComments: Large depression collects snow and run off with ephemeral stream, only a tiny pool surrounding stream found with no frogs/tadpoles
visitDirections: Drive to end of "Dunham Lot" road, use GPS to go uphill to "pool"
visitHabitatComment: Heavy snow in winter with run off and a wet spring would produce a bigger pool. This year was a very dry spring
visitSpeciesComments: no frogs or tadpole etc seen
Seep, not a VP.

visitDirections: Park along Crosstown Rd near Boyer State Forest Sign, access up and thru- bushwack following GPS.
visitHabitatComment: pool substrate is sedge peat
visitSpeciesComments: Perched sedge meadow pool, surrounding forest all young pole sized- either clearcut or old pasture. Extensive willow/dogwood shrubs. Pool emergents Carex utriculata(?), Equisetum fluviatile, Glyceria sp., Calamagrostis canadensis.

visitDirections: Park near Boyer State Forest sign off Crosstown rd. Access up and thru, long bushwack- maybe better access from E?
visitSpeciesOther2: predaceous diving beetle larvae, daphnia, dobsonfly larvae, phantom midge
visitSpeciesComments: Big Classic pool, very active and productive with abundant larvae for both SPSA and WOFR, Jeffersons eggs uncertain, degraded but seemed likely- must have been many more SPSA eggs, to big and deep to see many parts.

visitDirections: Park on Crosstown Rd near Boyer State Forest sign, cross field, bushwack following GPs to site.
visitHabitatComment: Pool is an old granite quarry. No logging evidence, but old quarry debris piles everywhere, old trail/road within 40ft of pool edge.
visitSpeciesComments: Series of 3 stepped old quarry pools in close proximity, dimensions given for all together. Ground water seepage feeds top pool, overflows successively to lower pools. Very productive pools.

visitDirections: Drive up Slaughterhouse road as far as possible (currently washed out). Park, hike rest of way up road to camp, follow trails and bushwack to site
visitHabitatComment: Grassland/ hay meadow to east. Pine plantation to south and east.
visitSpeciesComments: Large winterberry patch in pool, floating debris mat in middle(with many seedlings). Pine needles abundant on pool surface/ in substrate. Scirpus and Sparganium spp.in pool.

visitDirections: Park along Union Brook Rd. Bushwack to site near power cut, follow GPS.
visitHabitatComment: future cut marked nearby apparently with reasonable buffer
visitSpeciesComments: Nice classic pool in somewhat seepy opening. Other small pools nearby. Big Predacious diving beetle larvae eating tadpoles!

visitDirections: Park on Terry Hill Rd near where corner of parcel touches road, follow GPS to point, near field edge with neighboring parcel.
visitHabitatComment: very old stumps on pool edge. open field within 50ft of one edge with house further away in field. Pool is just inside Norwich property boundary.Spruce/Hemlock forest around
visitSpeciesComments: Likely many more SPSA, visibility very obscured by duckweed, scum and fibrous aquatic moss. Pool edge with lots of Sphagnum, cinnamon fern and an "island" of black? spruce, blueberry, Nemopanthus mucronata. Nice pool!!

visitDirections: SW of Paine Mt.
visitPoolType: Pool associated with larger wetland complex
visitHabitatComment: Shallow pool that grades into large open, seepy wetland, where a large bull moose was feeding.
visitSpeciesComments: Probably provides limited productivity for amphibians due to shallow depth, lots of algae, ferns, and emergent veg.

visitDirections: SW of Paine Mt.
visitHabitatComment: Linear pool in narrow topographic slot between rock outcroppings.  Water was tannin stained.
visitSpeciesComments: Wood Frog tadpoles were abundant; there were also well-developed Ambystoma salamander larvae (~0.5" long) with large heads that I suspect were Jeffersons, especially since Spotted sal. egg masses were still unhatched.

visitDirections: Leaving from Northfield town forest trail, bushwacked through woods to find pool using GPS.
visitSpeciesComments: Egg mass count may be significantly understestimated due to floating vegetation and inability to see into interior portions of the pool.

visitDirections: Pool was reached by bushwacking through woods using GPS device to locate pool
visitHabitatComment: Pool is on an old skidder road.  Pool is exposed to full sun with grasses around the pool in old skidder roadway.
visitSpeciesComments: Many spotted salamander egg masses were exposed due to pool drying.  Approximately 30 exposed egg masses were counted, and 6 submersed egg masses were observed in the pool.  Many tadpoles.  No salamander larva seen.

visitDirections: Leaving town forest trail, bushwacked through woods to find pool using GPS.
visitHabitatComment: Water quite tannic.  About 50% shaded at midday.  West side formed by a rock outcrop.  Old skidder road at north end.  Could be permanent hydroperiod (not sure).
visitSpeciesComments: Many tadpoles.  About 50 spotted salamander egg masses counted - more may have been present in pond interior (not visible).  Lots of caddis fly cases also observed.

visitDirections: South of Turkey Hill
visitHabitatComment: Nearly covered completely by duckweed.
visitSpeciesComments: Green frog calling.  Suspect that spotted salamander breeds here also but duckweed and pool size limited visibility.

visitDirections: Abt. 800 ft. North of Barrows Road just below high point in road.
visitHabitatComment: All physical and locational attributes the same as 2011 except pool is totally dry this year, 2012.
visitSpeciesComments: Last year (2011) at this time this pool was full with a maximum depth of 2-3 feet, wood frogs, spotted salamanders and fairy shrimp present. This year (2012) it is completely dry without any evidence of moisture or ponding.

visitDirections: Park at owners house at end of Tamarack Farm Rd (extensive posted signs/warnings), but owner is friendly. Follow their tractor trail across field and up to the ridgline.
visitSpeciesComments: poor visibility. Very herbaceous covered with cinnamon, royal, sensitive ferns, rhizomatous Scirpus sp. and Carex tussocks. hummocky, deep muck. Ridgetop pool w/ rich N. hardwood stand below, on adjoining parcel based on fenceline - never surveyed.

visitLocationComments: Had permission from Newelle Freere, may not be correct owner- no one home at time of visit.

visitDirections: N of Lakota Rd.

visitHabitatComment: Large ridge top vernal pool complex. Surrounding forest (mostly hemlock) has been selectively logged in past. Tannic water. One pool crossed by old dirt logging road, it is deeper here and this is where I see the most adult salamanders on migration night.

visitDirections: Drive up McKain rd as far as possible (currently washed out)park follow up to camp/house, follow trails and bushwack to site.
visitHabitatComment: minor cutting ~100m away
visitSpeciesComments: Extremely tannic water impaired visibility, surprisingly egg rich for size. Surrounded by dense spruce saplings. Other obvious pools to north on property are old beaver ponds- checked one superabundant Spotteds egg masses but also large rainbow trout!

visitDirections: not sure of formal access. I parked on Bliss Pond Rd to the south and accessed acrossed private land following GPS to site.
visitHabitatComment: another smaller, less productive pool very nearby.
visitSpeciesOther2: predaceous diving beetle larvae, adult green frogs, daphnia, copepods, aquatic red mites
visitSpeciesComments: Very nice classic pool, abundant tadpoles. Nice black ash in pool emerging from water. Another smaller pool close by

visitDirections: Park along Lightening Ridge Rd at trail access to Chickering fen (small TNC sign on south side of road). Follow access trail to fen then follow small footpath south to pool.
visitHabitatComment: Other wetlands nearby but not obviously connected. TNC Preserve.
visitSpeciesOther2: Green frogs and Red spotted newts
visitSpeciesComments: Fenny pool with peaty bottom and a mat of emergent Carex lasiocarpa in places. Abundant willow, dogwood and spiraea shrubs in pool, other emergents include: Onoclea sensibilis, Iris versicolor, Glyceria sp, Sparganium sp., Calliergon moss

visitDirections: Park at owners house (2141 Lower Rd) follow GPS to site.
visitPoolType: Pool associated with larger wetland complex
visitHabitatComment: Surrounding area open toward north end, overgrown pasture. Forested at south end.
visitSpeciesComments: old beaver sign around pool including small old lodge at pool edge. Pool crosses property boundary to south (no contact with that owner). Pool grades into shrub swamp of willows and reed canary grass. SPSA eggs all hatched

visitDirections: Park on Gonyeau Rd. near intersection with Middle Rd.Pool visible from road down the embankment.
visitHabitatComment: No obligate indicators found but could have fairy shrimp if checked early, unlikely to support amphibians, very short hydroperiod.
visitDisturbOther: possible digging/ culvert  according to owner
visitSpeciesComments: Very short hydroperiod, could support fairy shrimp, but too late to tell. owner and neighbors say it holds water early. Roads on 2 sides. Rich hardwood forest adjacent, including sugarbush.

visitLocationComments: Owner took me to many pools within property- this is probably the one that corresponds to the potential point.
visitDirections: Park along Middle Rd. next junction with Gonyeau, by cable strung between trees. Follow path behind cable and GPS to pool.
visitPoolType: Pool associated with larger wetland complex
visitHabitatComment: Past logging up to pool edge maybe 10-15 yrs ago. Larger wetland area is innundated early and owner has seen eggs in many places, currently only along one deeper, less vegetated edge that may be the smaller more functional pool habitat.
visitSpeciesComments: Owner says Jeff/blue spot hybrids known from property because Susan Sawyer (project volunteer) hatched out eggs from the site and Ided the larvae. Owner also says hes seen wood frogs in the pool in past, but none observed.

visitDirections: Park along Middle Rd.  Follow GPS, some trails from adjoining Clark Property lead nearby.
visitHabitatComment: Was cleared up to pool edge in past, now all dense small pole timber. Pool sits between bedrocks ledges
visitSpeciesComments: Visibility highly obscured by almost total duckweed cover. Neighbor and project volunteer,Allen Clark, says it is very productive, especially of frogs, and suspects a spring underneath keeps it full all year.
